content:
Carrier filtering is the practice where carriers block the delivery of some or all of the messaging from a specific number or business. To provide the best messaging solution for your customers, you must understand how and when carrier filtering occurs.

Standard SMS channels are scheduled for retirement, and weâ€™re limiting the ability to create standard channels. To avoid service interruptions, upgrade your standard SMS channels to enhanced channels before February 14, 2026.

The following are some of the main reasons for filtering:

To comply with the carrier's policies, or with state, local, or country-specific regulations.
To enforce rules and regulations that protect mobile subscribers from unwanted or unsolicited messaging.
To prevent P2P messages from being sent through A2P streams, and to prevent A2P messages from using P2P routes.
To reduce the potential for dissatisfied customers who file complaints, take legal action, seek damages, or switch to another carrier for loss of business.

Filtering techniques can vary from one carrier and country to the next. Filters can be triggered any number of ways, such as from a defined list of terms or from advanced logic with the use of adaptive software systems and machine learning.

To familiarize yourself with country rules and regulations, refer to SMS Regulations by Country. Because regulations can change, we recommend a legal review of the regulatory bodies that govern the telecommunications systems in the country or territory where you plan to do business.

Best practices to protect against filtering include:

Learn the rules and regulations of your target market.
Provide clear and easy opt-out instructions.
Avoid URLs.
Personalize the content.
Limit the amount and ratio of messaging for P2P.
Understand the messaging hours of operation of the target audience.
Keep messaging professional and clearly identify the sender.

If your messages were incorrectly blocked or filtered, you can verify that messages aren't blocked by each of the major carriers. To confirm filtering, test against all major carriers.
title: SMS Carrier Filtering Practices
